1 Pre-Processing

The following steps prepare the dataset for the modeling part. The actual feature analysis was done in another kernel.

2 Modeling

Multivariate Adaptive Regression Splines (MARS) is a generalization of stepwise linear regression. The procedure systematically creates a suitable set of basis expansions for the predictors which will then be linearly regressed. Basis functions are hinge functions. The number and positioning of knots is flexible. Similar to the CART method, the algorithm works by first building a very complex model and then pruning it to avoid overfitting.

Here, the earth package is used, which is a very easy to use implementation of the MARS procedure by Stephen Milborrow.

2.1 Preparation

The dataset is split back into training and test.

train <- full[label == "train", !"label"]
test <- full[label == "test", !c("label", "SalePrice")]
X <- train[, !"SalePrice"]
Y <- train$SalePrice

Instead of using all features one could also use the set of features labelled important by the Boruta analysis. Then, the binary features could be added or removed from either set.

Ximp <- X[, impVars, with = FALSE]
Xsmall <- X[, c(impVars, binVars), with = FALSE]

2.2 Training

Training is done in a forward pass and a pruning step. In general the forward pass should create a model of sufficiently high complexity. The pruning step should then simplify the model again to reduce overfitting.

During the forward pass there are a few conditions which define when the model has reached a high enough complexity. Two of them are a maximum number of terms and a threshold in residual sum of squares gain (RSS). Here, the maximum number of terms is always set very high (200). Thereby, the forward pass only stops when no increase in RSS by more than 0.001 is gained.

The models performance on the training dataset can be read mainly from the \(R^2\) (RSq) and generalized \(R^2\) (GRSq). In GRSq there is a penalty for model complexity which is estimated by the number of terms, knots and interactions in the model. Furthermore residual and quantile-quantile plots, and cummulative distributions of residuals can be used to see the models performance.

The maximum GRSq value is also used for finding an appropriate model size during the pruning step. Instead of using the GRSq, a cross-validation estimated \(R^2\) can be used as well. However, this is computationally too expensive for this kernel. GRSq usually finds roughly the same model size anyway.

Additive

First, an additive model of hinge functions is created by not allowing interaction terms.

fit <- earth(X, Y, nk = 200)
fit
## Selected 19 of 22 terms, and 11 of 209 predictors
## Termination condition: RSq changed by less than 0.001 at 22 terms
## Importance: OverallQual, YearBuilt, GrLivArea, OverallCond, ...
## Number of terms at each degree of interaction: 1 18 (additive model)
## GCV 0.01605802    RSS 22.27148    GRSq 0.8994307    RSq 0.9043324
plot(fit)

Interaction

Next, 2nd degree interaction terms are allowed.

fit <- earth(X, Y, nk = 200, degree = 2)
fit
## Selected 36 of 42 terms, and 22 of 209 predictors
## Termination condition: RSq changed by less than 0.001 at 42 terms
## Importance: OverallQual, YearBuilt, GrLivArea, OverallCond, ...
## Number of terms at each degree of interaction: 1 15 20
## GCV 0.01198242    RSS 15.43772    GRSq 0.9249557    RSq 0.9336869
plot(fit)

2.3 Model Selection

Here, model selection can be directly done with the expected prediction error of the learning procedure. This will be done using cross validation. The root-mean-squared-error (RMSE) of the log of the target variable is defined as error.

L <- function(Y, Yh) sqrt(sum((Y - Yh)^2) / length(Y))

Inside the cross validation a prediction function will train a MARS model on one part of the training set and then predict the other. The RMSE for the prediction will be returned.

predMARS <- function(trainX, trainY, testX, testY, ...) {
  fit <- earth(trainX, trainY, nk = 200, ...)
  pred <- predict(fit, newdata = testX)
  return(L(testY, pred[, 1]))
}

Splitting of the data and execution of the prediction function is performed by crossval. For each model it will repeat a 5-fold cross validation 10 times. The resulting mean RMSE and its standard error are stored in a list.

CV <- list()
CV$Add <- crossval(predMARS, X, Y, 
                   verbose = FALSE, K = 5, B = 10)
CV$Add_imp <- crossval(predMARS, Ximp, Y, 
                       verbose = FALSE, K = 5, B = 10)
CV$Add_small <- crossval(predMARS, Xsmall, Y, 
                         verbose = FALSE, K = 5, B = 10)
# CV$Int <- crossval(predMARS, X, Y, degree = 2, 
#                    verbose = FALSE, K = 5, B = 10)
# CV$Int_imp <- crossval(predMARS, Ximp, Y, degree = 2, 
#                        verbose = FALSE, K = 5, B = 10)
# CV$Int_small <- crossval(predMARS, Xsmall, Y, degree = 2, 
#                          verbose = FALSE, K = 5, B = 10)

Cases with interaction terms take to long to compute on kaggle, so they are commented out. Overall they performed worse than their additive counterparts. Estimated RMSEs for all models are shown below.

l <- lapply(CV, function(i) data.frame(RMSE = i$stat, se = i$stat.se))
res <- do.call(rbind, l)
res$Model <- rownames(res)
ggplot(res, aes(x = Model, y = RMSE)) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(ymax = RMSE + se, ymin = RMSE - se), color = "blue") +
  coord_flip() +
  ggtitle("CV-Estimated RMSE with Standard Error") +
  theme_classic()

The summary shows the terms in the order they were added during the forward pass. 2 hinge functions for OverallQual and GrLivArea were added first. These were also the most important features identified by the Boruta analysis.

Another way to estimate the variable importance is by looking at the number of terms in which they were used. This is shown below in the column nsubsets. The order of variables changed here compared to the summary.

3 Prediction

Finally the test set can be predicted.

Xtest <- test[, impVars, with = FALSE]
pred <- predict(fit, newdata = Xtest)[, 1]

The actual prices are shown below.

prices <- exp(pred)
summary(prices)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   48430  127500  158400  178700  211200  728700
ggplot(data.frame(Yh = prices), aes(x = Yh)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30) +
  scale_x_continuous(trans = "log10") +
  theme_bw()
